  <recipe>
    <name>Merlin's Lentil Dhal</name>
    <source>http://www.jamieoliver.com/news-and-features/features/lentils-and-basic-tarka-dhal-recipe/#VCetYpGK5UV4Jm1G.97</source>
    <preparation>Place the lentils in a pan and cover with enough cold water to come around
two inches above their suface. Bring to boil (skim off any scum that rises to the top),
and reduce the a simmer. Stir in the turmeric and a generous knob of butter.
Cover and leave to cook gently.

In a small frying pan, dry-fry the cumin seeds over a medium heat until toasted
and fragrant (no more than a couple of minutes). Remove from the pan and set
to one side.

Melt a second knob of butter in the same frying pan and gently fry the chopped
garlic, onion, chillies and the grated ginger and tomatoes, if you are using them.
Once the garlic is golden, mix in the toasted cumin seeds and, if using, the
garam masal and ground coriander. Remove from the heat until the lentils are
completely softened.

Give the lentils a good stir. They should have the conistency of porridge - thicker
than soup and looser than houmous. Add more water as neccessary (you will be 
surprised how thick they can get over just a couple of extra minutes cooking),
and mix in your aromatic fried mixture.

Season to taste, then serve on its own, topped with coriander, or with a side of
basmati rice and greens.</preparation>
    <portions>4</portions>
    <cook>Merlin Jobst</cook>
